1
00:00:00,125 --> 00:00:01,625
They were annoyed with us

2
00:00:01,916 --> 00:00:03,125
But that happens

3
00:00:03,583 --> 00:00:06,875
Because you’re not one of their members

4
00:00:07,125 --> 00:00:10,083
Considering you’re in that place with them

5
00:00:10,625 --> 00:00:14,833
He tells you—We’re fighting for you, doing this and that, and we have martyrs

6
00:00:15,041 --> 00:00:18,125
We’re fighting in battles and you’re sitting here, you’re supposed to be with your brothers

7
00:00:18,250 --> 00:00:22,333
And so on, and he keeps talking, trying to convince you

8
00:00:22,875 --> 00:00:25,000
He wants to get that idea into your head and thinking

9
00:00:25,291 --> 00:00:26,916
Interviewer: How many guards were in the room with you?

10
00:00:28,166 --> 00:00:29,250
For us, there were two

11
00:00:29,958 --> 00:00:32,916
The guys called one Abu... I don’t remember his name

12
00:00:33,875 --> 00:00:34,875
And the other, Abu Shalaan

13
00:00:35,250 --> 00:00:37,875
Interviewer: Did they take shifts or were they together?

14
00:00:38,208 --> 00:00:40,083
No, each one separately, and sometimes both came

15
00:00:40,208 --> 00:00:43,166
And sometimes one would come, knock on the door, and say—We’re not hearing you anymore

16
00:00:44,041 --> 00:00:46,375
You’re not reading the Quran anymore, and so on

17
00:00:47,208 --> 00:00:52,333
Interviewer: During your time there, over twenty-four hours a day

18
00:00:52,791 --> 00:00:54,583
Were they the same ones or did they change?

19
00:00:54,625 --> 00:00:56,083
No, they changed, they changed

20
00:00:56,166 --> 00:00:57,500
Interviewer: How often did they change?

21
00:00:57,583 --> 00:01:02,000
Every two days, they didn’t stay in the same place

22
00:01:03,791 --> 00:01:07,916
Interviewer: Did the guards here participate in battles?

23
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,875
Did they go out, return, and take part in fighting and support?

24
00:01:11,750 --> 00:01:13,416
When would they go out and come back?

25
00:01:13,791 --> 00:01:16,416
Sometimes there were alerts

26
00:01:17,250 --> 00:01:20,791
At times we’d say there’s no one here except us

27
00:01:20,916 --> 00:01:22,416
Especially when the airstrikes came

28
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,541
We’d say only the prisoners might be here, we couldn’t hear their voices

29
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:29,291
Then after three or four hours

30
00:01:29,583 --> 00:01:32,166
They might come, and you’d hear them moving back and forth

31
00:01:33,458 --> 00:01:35,416
Interviewer; Did you see yourselves as targeted?

32
00:01:35,500 --> 00:01:37,875
We were targeted, targeted one hundred percent

33
00:01:38,375 --> 00:01:40,916
Targeted—if not by them, then by the planes overhead

34
00:01:41,708 --> 00:01:43,958
We didn’t know in which minute we’d be struck

35
00:01:44,333 --> 00:01:49,916
Interviewer: While you were there and the planes arrived, they would withdraw from the whole building

36
00:01:50,208 --> 00:01:52,458
Did you expect that?

37
00:01:52,583 --> 00:01:55,083
Honestly, at times I

38
00:01:55,166 --> 00:01:58,458
Interviewer: Did you have a sense of what was happening outside and so on?

39
00:01:58,583 --> 00:02:02,291
Sometimes we heard the heavy sound of planes

40
00:02:03,041 --> 00:02:05,083
Here we didn’t hear any sound, there was no one

41
00:02:06,708 --> 00:02:10,416
We would say they’d left us here and we would be bombed while they were gone

42
00:02:12,125 --> 00:02:15,375
In that situation you don’t know what you will do, you are terrified

43
00:02:16,208 --> 00:02:21,916
Even when sleeping, you wake up suddenly from the planes, something terrifying

44
00:02:22,750 --> 00:02:29,000
Interviewer: Do they disappear from the building before you hear the planes, or while the planes are overhead do they vanish?

45
00:02:29,333 --> 00:02:33,833
As soon as the planes started flying, you didn’t hear any movement from them

46
00:02:34,166 --> 00:02:38,000
Interviewer: Do you think they knew the planes were coming?

47
00:02:38,125 --> 00:02:39,125
Honestly, I don’t know

48
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:43,833
In my view, they knew about it

49
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:45,666
I remember it happened to us two or three times

50
00:02:45,708 --> 00:02:51,083
And I said it was likely this building would be bombed, and they left us alone in it and departed

51
00:02:51,541 --> 00:02:52,833
We were desperate about that situation

52
00:02:53,125 --> 00:02:56,916
Interviewer: If this building, as they thought, was targeted

53
00:02:57,250 --> 00:03:02,333
Why didn’t they try to move you to another place if this building was targeted?

54
00:03:03,208 --> 00:03:04,208
Why didn’t they try to move you?

55
00:03:04,291 --> 00:03:10,291
One time we were here, and during the lesson heavy plane activity started

56
00:03:11,750 --> 00:03:16,625
He said—Immediately end the lesson and return every prisoner to his place

57
00:03:18,666 --> 00:03:20,333
Within a minute they dispersed quickly

58
00:03:21,416 --> 00:03:22,666
Meaning they even ended the lesson

59
00:03:22,791 --> 00:03:25,625
Interviewer: So he ordered them to disperse? Witness: Yes, to disperse
